## Original paper methodology

The paper aimed to simulate an environment through AVIDA such that organisms living in cells will evolve the ability to communicate. This would be encouraged by rewarding sending messages between one another containing the highest cell-ID that each organism knows of, and the goal is for 95% of the messages to carry the highest cell ID. Each organism can only send and receive a message if 2 organisms are facing each other, but they have the capability to turn themselves left and right, but the knowledge of when to do so will need to be evolved

The specifics of the AVIDA environment is that of a 60 x 60 torus, run for 100,000 of AVIDA’s standard time units called updates. During a single update, each organism can execute on average 30 of its virtual CPU instructions. Organisms can reproduce by copying their own genome, with a 0.75% chance for any instruction to be mutated during the process, as well as a 5% chance of randomly adding or removing a genome from the offspring. The authors ran 20 trials for each of 3 experiments, each experiment having a different set of tasks that reward or penalize CPU cycles from an organism.

The tasks developed for this study were:

* SEND \- SELF 

  * Rewards sending a message containing the sender’s cell-ID.

* SEND \- ID 

  * Rewards sending a message containing any cell-ID.

* MAX \- KNOWN 

  * Rewards sending a message containing the largest value known, defined as M ax(self, M ax(msg0, ...msgn)), where {msg0, ...msgn} is the set of all messages  eceived by that organism. The sender must have received at least one message prior to being rewarded for performing this task.

* SEND \- NON \- ID 

  * Penalizes the sender of a message that does not carry a cell-ID.

(Directed Evolution of Communication and Cooperation in Digital Organisms)

## Original Results I attempted to Replicate

The first experiment of the paper tested for the hypothesis that “rewarding organisms for sending messages containing cell-IDs, where the cell-ID carried is greater than the organism’s own cell-ID, will eventually result in all messages in the population carrying the largest cell-ID”. In the end, the organisms didn’t send the largest cell-ID, but managed to send messages containing cell-IDs greater than their own.

![][image1]

Here, Carry is the number of messages sent that carry a cell-ID; ID is the number of messages sent that carry the sender’s cell-ID; and \>ID is the number of messages sent that carry a cell-ID greater than the sender’s.

The second experiment was run with the MAX \- KNOWN , SEND \- ID , and the penalty SEND \- NON \- ID. The results is as follows:

![][image2]

All in all, the number of messages actually carrying IDs increased by a lot. Later on, with SEND - SELF, the number of organisms sending the highest cell-ID increased to 98.3%. 

## Description of your reimplementation and any changes 

To replicate the first experiment, I had to write my own implementation of how organisms can communicate. To stick as close to AVIDA’s targeted messaging as possible, I implemented a new Cell class that holds various parameters such as the Cell ID, the direction the organism in it is facing, and a vector of pointers to the surrounding cells. I added methods that checked for if organisms are facing each other, as well as adding into their CPU spaces to hold the message they have just received, the list of messages they have received throughout their lives, as well as what the organism is planning to send. This allowed me to closely approximate, at least on the surface, for AVIDA organisms handle messages, as well as setting up data monitors that got triggered whenever the conditions of sending a message are met: the SendMessage custom instruction is triggered, and the current organism is facing another organism who’s also facing them.

I also tried to replicate the MAX \- KNOWN and SEND \- ID tasks and used them as a basis of awarding them points. Since I’m doing this in Empirical World, I lack the skill to implement the extended CPU cycles reward mechanism on my own, and instead use points what organisms can use to reproduce instead. AVIDA organisms can reproduce by themselves indefinitely, but in order to both fill my cells with organisms and have the points be the criteria of competition, I let each organism receive continuous free points until they have reproduced twice, so that it’s highly likely that all cells would eventually be occupied. Furthermore, I only have mutations happening in replicated genomes and not via insertion or deletion, as I lacked the knowledge to do so.

## Results so far

My web version is showing poor performance, as my organisms only seems to pass non-ids up until the 1300s cycles. The singular numbers being sent told me they were likely to have initially been sending the direction they are facing, which is a retrievable piece of data through a custom instruction I added to mimic the capabilities of AVIDA organisms in the paper. Sadly, my task implementations have proven to be faulty, as custom print statements guaranteeing reports when any message is passed doesn’t coordinate with what the data monitors keeping track of the tasks’ successes. Furthermore, my native version somehow doesn’t trigger any instructions or data monitors at all. I checked this by running a method that only runs on a successful message being sent, connected to a data monitor, and the printed datafile lacked any showing of the forced triggers.

As a result, I am not sure of the exact details of my web version’s happenings. I sadly lack the time to work on a custom data output using the web version and analyze it after spending too much time trying to debug the tasks and the native file. Still, my results seem to be following the trends shown in the original papers, as both non-ids and cell-ids are being sent. Once again, however, I lacked the time to completely verify my claim.

## Attempted Expansions

To further encourage reproduction, I introduced a longevity penalty, where in every update, an organism will lose points proportional to the number of digits of their age, with their age defined as the number of updates that organism has lived for. I believe this will further increase the chance of frequent reproductions, and thus mutations, as well as killing off organisms that evolved to be silent in order to avoid losing points via the SEND \- NON \- ID tasks. A more basic but very impactful expansion I did was the implementation of a config board that allows for the adjustment of the mutation rate.

The addition of the longevity penalty finally produced some good results. For the first experiment, my organisms started sending some existing cell-ID starting around the 800th update cycle, and the same happened with the second experiment replication. I trust my custom print statements more than my attempts at implementing data files since I understand how they work better.
